<span id="freeTextContainer11045279613540708086">As the 150 anniversary of the Battle of Antietam approaches, I&apos;m trying to refamilarize myself with the lay of land so to speak and the title of this book gives one pause as to the carnage inflicted on a single September on a battlefield in near a creak by the town called Sharpsburg. I&apos;ve only got past the introduction but for the Union and for Lincoln in general, the War was going very very wrong.<br/><br/>Since the elevation of command from relative obscurity from military advisor to the President of th</span>
  <span id="freeText11045279613540708086" style="display:none">As the 150 anniversary of the Battle of Antietam approaches, I'm trying to refamilarize myself with the lay of land so to speak and the title of this book gives one pause as to the carnage inflicted on a single September on a battlefield in near a creak by the town called Sharpsburg. I've only got past the introduction but for the Union and for Lincoln in general, the War was going very very wrong.<br /><br />Since the elevation of command from relative obscurity from military advisor to the President of the Confederacy and of fortifications in Georgia, General Robert E. Lee has throughly beaten a Union Army approaching the gates of Richmond, capital of the CSA. Lincoln has resorted to firing Generals and reorganizing commands but everywhere, even in the West (Mississippi and Tennessee)the Confederate armies run victorious. <br /><br />More frightening however, is the prospect of Europe interceding in the conflict. Parties in Britain and France (led by not as able nephew of Napoleon, Napoleon III)are itching to spread their influence and bloody the nose of the upstart Americans. One more rousing victory may give the doubting Thomas's in both countries pause to support such an endeavor as involvement in the American war.<br /><br />And so 150 years or so ago, General Robert E. Lee and the Army of Northern Virginia disappear. General Pope, the latest in series of mediocre Generals, has lost contact with main body of the enemy in front of him. General McClellan, Commander, Army of the Potomac, is moving his forces from the disastrous summmer's Peninsula Campaign by sea back to the confines near Washington. It is a dangerous time for our Republic. Discontent is growing in the North, our Armies either statemated or worse, and Europe is eyeing with avarice to intervene. All this and no one can ascertain just where in the hell Bobby Lee and his Army have gone. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11045279613540708086" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


