<div id="review_87899798" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/87899798" />
    <a title="Ben Vogel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3193966-ben-vogel"><img alt="Ben Vogel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298665354p2/3193966.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/87899798?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben Vogel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben Vogel" href="/user/show/3193966-ben-vogel">Ben Vogel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer87899798" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12545773218188236477">Any book on Antietam is going to have two guaranteed elements; a primer on the origins and issuance of the emancipation proclamation and a thorough indictment on the ego and hesitancy of General George B McClellan. This book serves well in the first instance and doubles down on the second. Indeed it could easily be subtitled: The Worst General in the World or some similar construction. Sears despises McClellan, and if you didn&apos;t share in that opinion to begin with, he will go a long way toward c</span>
  <span id="freeText12545773218188236477" style="display:none">Any book on Antietam is going to have two guaranteed elements; a primer on the origins and issuance of the emancipation proclamation and a thorough indictment on the ego and hesitancy of General George B McClellan. This book serves well in the first instance and doubles down on the second. Indeed it could easily be subtitled: The Worst General in the World or some similar construction. Sears despises McClellan, and if you didn't share in that opinion to begin with, he will go a long way toward convincing you by the end.<br /><br />This is likely the finest work on the Battle of Antietam. If I have any criticism of the book at all, I wish it spent more time on the actual events on the day of the battle. Other works can fill in those gaps. Landscape Turned Red paints the complete picture of the campaign and its impacts upon the course of the war and the nature of the conflict.<br /><br />Re-read May ‘18. Terrific book. Sears has a gift in his telling of history. I hope to read all of his books eventually.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12545773218188236477" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


