<span id="freeTextContainer15235872995451233320">Best book I have read, and re read on the Battle of Antietam. I first read this book in the 1980s and have now just re read it in 2016. Antietam is one of the big battles of the Civil War where the North had a big chance to pull off a big victory, but didnt. Due to General George Mcclellans timid generalship. The result of the limited Union victory allowed Lincoln to issue the Emancipation proclimation, freeing the slaves, and also giving pause to Englands thoughts of intervention. A very bloody</span>
  <span id="freeText15235872995451233320" style="display:none">Best book I have read, and re read on the Battle of Antietam. I first read this book in the 1980s and have now just re read it in 2016. Antietam is one of the big battles of the Civil War where the North had a big chance to pull off a big victory, but didnt. Due to General George Mcclellans timid generalship. The result of the limited Union victory allowed Lincoln to issue the Emancipation proclimation, freeing the slaves, and also giving pause to Englands thoughts of intervention. A very bloody day, in fact the bloodiest day of the war. Lee was repulsed from Union soil in Maryland and forced to retire due to his losses. The Union failed to follow up, and possibly bring greatet harm to the Confederacy. Thus allowing Lee to regroup. The book explores the lost order, Burnsides Bridge. the battles of the cornfields, the sunken lane and the woods. First person accounts, and good narrative tell a very good version of events.</span>
